1 6. An incident involving multiple deaths or injuries in a short amount of
2 time.
3 (b) Any firefighter or rescue squad member involved directly in a critical
4 incident may take up to forty-eight (48) hours of leave immediately following
5 a critical incident. This leave may commence upon:
6 1. The completion of that firefighter or rescue squad
7 member's[firefighter's] shift encompassing the critical incident, or when
8 all necessary administrative procedures relating to a critical incident
9 have been completed; and
10 2. The firefighter or rescue squad member informs his or her supervisor.
11 (c) For regular firefighters, this leave may be unpaid or paid leave. The pay status
12 is to be determined by the firefighter's employment contract, collective labor
13 agreement if any, or by written departmental policy. This subsection shall not
14 be construed to set aside any employment contract, labor agreement, or
15 departmental policies that grant more than forty-eight (48) hours of leave
16 following an officer involved critical incident.
17 (d) For volunteer firefighters, this leave may be unpaid or paid leave. The pay
18 status is to be determined by the firefighter's written departmental policy.
19 (e) For rescue squad members, this leave may be unpaid or paid leave. The pay
20 status is to be determined by a written policy of the Division of Emergency
21 Management.
22 SECTION 2. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 39F IS CREATED TO
23 READ AS FOLLOWS:
24 The division shall enter into an agreement with the Kentucky Fire Commission to
25 provide rescue squad members with access to the program under Section 1 of this Act.
26 Section 3. This Act may be cited as Gavin's Rights.
